Exercise 1 -

In this first exercise we will be running a simple regression to predict time from track. As you can see below, there are 16 different tracks. Unlike with t-tests, we do NOT have to limit it to two levels. However, we do need to think about what our reference group will be. Generally, the reference group is either a baseline (because all other levels will be compared to it) or it is the level you are most interested in. In addition, we want to be thoughtful of our levels, do we really need to look at all 13? Or can we narrow it down to the 5 tracks of most interest?

Below we can see all 16 tracks.

mario$track <- as.factor(mario$track)
levels(mario$track)
##  [1] "Banshee Boardwalk"     "Bowser's Castle"       "Choco Mountain"       
##  [4] "D.K.'s Jungle Parkway" "Frappe Snowland"       "Kalimari Desert"      
##  [7] "Koopa Troopa Beach"    "Luigi Raceway"         "Mario Raceway"        
## [10] "Moo Moo Farm"          "Rainbow Road"          "Royal Raceway"        
## [13] "Sherbet Land"          "Toad's Turnpike"       "Wario Stadium"        
## [16] "Yoshi Valley"

I am only interested in the following tracks: Banshee Boardwalk, Bowserâs Castle, Rainbow Road, Wario Stadium, and Yoshi Valley.

Below I filter the dataset to only include data for these 5 tracks.

mario <- mario %>%
  filter(track == "Banshee Boardwalk" |
           track == "Bowser's Castle" |
           track == "Yoshi Valley" |
           track == "Wario Stadium" |
           track == "Rainbow Road" )
mario$track <- droplevels(mario$track)
levels(mario$track)
## [1] "Banshee Boardwalk" "Bowser's Castle"   "Rainbow Road"     
## [4] "Wario Stadium"     "Yoshi Valley"

Right now, Banshee Boardwalk is the default reference level. We know this because it is the first level that appears above. I want to change the reference level to Bowser's Castle. I will do that in the below code.

mario$track <- relevel(mario$track, ref = "Bowser's Castle")

Below, I will confirm that Bowser's Castle is the new reference level.

levels(mario$track)
## [1] "Bowser's Castle"   "Banshee Boardwalk" "Rainbow Road"     
## [4] "Wario Stadium"     "Yoshi Valley"

Bowser's Castle shows up first and is now our reference level. We can now move on to our simple regression. Fill in the formula below to run a regression predicting time (the DV) from track (the IV). When you have correctly specified the lm() model, the summary(mod.mario.simple) will run without error.

mod.mario.simple <- lm(time ~ track, data = mario)
summary(mod.mario.simple)

Exercise 3 -

Now that we have run a simple regression (regression with just one IV) we want to now run a multiple regression. We want to run a new model that will add on a second IV: type

mario$type <- as.factor(mario$type)

## [1] "Single Lap" "Three Lap"

In this case, the reference level is Single Lap. I like this and will not change the reference level.

Now, it is time to build our multiple regression model. We will be predicting time (DV) from track (IV 1) AND type (IV 2). When you have correctly specified the lm() model, the summary(mod.mario.multiple) will run without error.

mod.mario.multiple <- lm(time ~ track + type, data = mario)

Multiple Regression: Alcohol Data Interactions

library(tidyverse)

alcohol <- read.csv("Data/alcohol.csv", stringsAsFactors = TRUE)

Exercise 9 - Cat & Num IVs interaction

We want to run a new model that used Sex as an independent variable.

levels(alcohol$Sex)
## [1] "Female" "Male"

In this case, the reference level is Female. I like this and will not change the reference level.

Now, it is time to build our multiple regression interaction model. We will be predicting Metabol (DV) from Sex (IV 1) AND Gastric (IV 2). When you have correctly specified the lm() model, the summary(alc.int.1) will run without error. This is running an Multiple Regression Model with main effects AND an interaction.

Metabol: firstâpass metabolism of alcohol in the stomach (in mmol/liter-hour)

Gastric: gastric alcohol dehydrogenase activity in the stomach (in Âµmol/min/g of tissue)

Sex: sex of the subject

alc.int.1 <- lm(Metabol ~ Gastric*Sex, alcohol)

summary(alc.int.1)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Metabol ~ Gastric * Sex, data = alcohol)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -2.4427 -0.6111 -0.0326  0.5436  3.8759 
## 
## Coefficients:
##                 Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)      -0.1973     0.1883  -1.047    0.295    
## Gastric           0.8369     0.1136   7.367 7.10e-13 ***
## SexMale          -0.9885     0.2518  -3.926 9.82e-05 ***
## Gastric:SexMale   1.5069     0.1313  11.480  < 2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 1.134 on 508 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.8137, Adjusted R-squared:  0.8126 
## F-statistic: 739.7 on 3 and 508 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

Your job is to interpret:

The intercept When the person is female and gastric is 0, the amount of metabolism of alcohol is predicted to be -0.1973.

All significant slopes (main effects only)

There is a significant main effect of gastric such that for every one unit increase in gastric alcohol dehydrogenase activity, the amount of metabolism of alcohol is predicted to icrease by 0.8369, (b = 0.8369, se = 0.11, p < 0.01).

There is a significant main effect of sex such that, in comparison to females, males are predicted to have a lower amount of metabolism of alcohol by -0.9885, (b = -0.9885, se = 0.25, p < 0.01).

Is there a significant interaction? There is a significant interaction effect of gastric and sex and the amount of metabolism of alcohol, (b = 1.5069, se = 0.1313, p < 0.01).

The Adjusted R-Squared Gastric & Sex account for 81% of the variance in the amount of metabolism of alcohol.

Exercise 10 -

Next we will visualize the multiple regression interaction model. I have provided some started code. Make sure you: set color = Sex, add a theme, label the x and y axes, and add a title. Interpret what you see and speak about the interaction. Is it a cross over interaction or a magnitude interaction?

ggplot(alcohol, aes(x = Gastric, y = Metabol, color = Sex)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, fullrange = TRUE) +
  theme_bw() +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Dark2") +
  labs(x = "Gastric Alcohol Dehydrogenase Activity in the Stomach", y = "Firstâpass Metabolism of Alcohol in the Stomach")

This is a magnitude interaction. When gastric is low, the difference of metabol is negligent between females and males. However, this effect increases as gastric increases such that when gastric is higher, males have much higher metabol than females.

Exercise 11 -

Now, it is time to build our multiple regression interaction model. We will be predicting Temperature (DV) from Age (IV 1) AND Weight (IV 2). When you have correctly specified the lm() model, the summary(temp.int.1) will run without error. This is running an Multiple Regression Model with main effects AND an interaction.

temp.int.1 <- lm(Temperature ~ Age*Weight, temp)

Your job is to interpret:

The intercept When age and weight are 0, core body temperature is predicted to be 36.67.

All significant slopes (main effects only)

There is significant main effecr of age such that for every 1 unit increase in age, core body temp is predicted to decrease by -0.003, (b = -0.003, se = 2.531e-04, p < 0.001).

Is there a significant interaction? There is a significant interaction of age and weight on core body temperature, (b = .00002, se = 3.548e-06, p < 0.001).

The Adjusted R-Squared Age and weight accounts for 51% of the variance in core body temperature.

Exercise 12 -

Next we will visualize the multiple regression interaction model. I have provided some started code.

Inside of the interact_plot() code: - set plot.points = TRUE - set x.label = âWeight (kg)â - set y.label = âBody Tempâ - set legend.main = âAgeâ

Outside of the interact_plot() code: - Add a â+â (like we do with ggplot2) - Add a theme

For help, look at the lecture video and code usring interact_plot().

Interpret what you see and speak about the interaction. Is it a cross over interaction or a magnitude interaction?

library(interactions)
interact_plot(model = temp.int.1, modx = Weight,
  pred = Age, modx.values = "plus-minus",
  plot.points = TRUE, x.label = "Weight (kg)",
  y.label = "Body Temp", modx.labels = c("Young", "Old"),
  legend.main = "Age",
  colors = "Dark2") +   #Using palette from https://www.datanovia.com/en/blog/the-a-z-of-rcolorbrewer-palette/
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") +
  geom_jitter(height = 0.01, alpha = .6)

This is a magnitude interactions. When weight is low, older and younger peoples have higher core temperature. When weight is high, older people have a higher core temperature compared to younger people.
